05041nam a22007695i 9780813595269DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135952697 a10.36019/97808135952692doi  a(DE-B1597)529937  a(OCoLC)1120696517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a973.04687284223/eng1 aAnastario, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParcels :bMemories of Salvadoran Migration /cMike Anastario. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b12 b-w  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatinidad: Transnational Cultures in the00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Diasporic Remembering -- t1. Es Barata y Es Cara: Couriers and Parcels in Transnational Space -- t2. A Sequence of Undocumented Migrant Memories -- t3. Diasporic Intimacy and Nostos Imaginaries -- t4. We Do Not Have to Learn to Be What We Are Not: Memory and Imagination in the Rural Diaspora -- tPart II: The U.S. Fugue State -- t5. Silence and Systematic Forgetting -- t6. Fields of Violence -- t7. Deferments of Voice, Myopic Reflections -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Research Methods -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn light of new proposals to control undocumented migrants in the United States, Parcels prioritizes rural Salvadoran remembering in an effort to combat the collective amnesia that supports the logic of these historically myopic strategies. Mike Anastario investigates the social memories of individuals from a town he refers to as "El Norteño," a rural municipality in El Salvador that was heavily impacted by the Salvadoran Civil War, which in turn fueled a mass exodus to the United States. By working with two viajeros (travelers) who exchanged encomiendas (parcels containing food, medicine, documents, photographs and letters) between those in the U.S. and El Salvador, Anastario tells the story behind parcels and illuminates their larger cultural and structural significance. This narrative approach elucidates key arguments concerning the ways in which social memory permits and is shaped by structural violence, particularly the U.S. actions and policies that have resulted in the emotional and physical distress of so many Salvadorans. The book uses analyses of testimonies, statistics, memories of migration, the war and, of course, the many parcels sent over the border to create an innovative and necessary account of post-Civil War El Salvador.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCollective memory. 0aEmigrant remittanceszEl Salvador. 0aSalvadoranszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813595269zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813595269423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813595269.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press